\section{Installing the file library}

The library image is copied from [[MLIB_SRC]] in this file to its
running location at [[MLIB_MLI]] ([[$B700]]--[[$BAFF]]), and pages
[[$B7]]--[[$B9]] are marked used in the ProDOS system bitmap so the
kernel will refuse to allocate buffers over the code. (Page [[$BA]]
holds the library's own variables and parameter blocks, and
[[MLIB_IOBUF]] at [[$BB00]]--[[$BEFF]] is its file buffer --- ProDOS
marks open-file buffers itself.)

On a 128K machine ([[GP_MACHID]] memory bits = 11) the first two bytes
of the \emph{auxiliary-bank} stack page are set to [[$FF]] --- scrubbing
state left there by the firmware so a later reset cannot vector through
it. Finally the library's default unit number is seeded from the boot
device in [[GP_DEVNUM]].

<<u1system install library>>=
        ORG $215C
SYS_INSTALL
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Copy the file library to $B700, protect it in the system
        ; bitmap, scrub the aux stack head on 128K machines, and seed
        ; the library's unit number from the boot device.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   MON_MOVE MLIB_SRC..MLIB_END -> $B700; mark pages $B7-$B9
        ;   in the bitmap; on 128K store #$FF at aux $0100/$0101;
        ;   MLIB_UNIT <- GP_DEVNUM. Falls into SYS_STARTUP.
        LDA #<MLIB_SRC
        STA MON_A1
        LDA #>MLIB_SRC
        STA MON_A1+1
        LDA #<MLIB_END
        STA MON_A2
        LDA #>MLIB_END
        STA MON_A2+1
        LDA #<MLIB_MLI
        STA MON_A4
        LDA #>MLIB_MLI
        STA MON_A4+1
        LDY #$00
        JSR MON_MOVE                    ; install the library at $B700
        LDA GP_BITMAP_B8
        ORA #$C0                        ; mark pages $B8,$B9 used
        STA GP_BITMAP_B8
        LDA GP_BITMAP_B0
        ORA #$01                        ; mark page $B7 used
        STA GP_BITMAP_B0
        LDA GP_MACHID
        AND #$30
        CMP #$30                        ; 128K machine?
        BNE .seed_unit
        LDA #$FF
        STA SET_ALTZP                   ; aux zero page/stack in
        STA $0100                       ; scrub aux stack head
        STA $0101
        STA SET_STDZP                   ; back to main bank
.seed_unit
        LDA GP_DEVNUM
        STA MLIB_UNIT                   ; library default device <- boot device
@ %def SYS_INSTALL

\section{Prefix setup and launch}

If no startup pathname was supplied (length byte zero), the launcher
reports ``Can't find a startup file.''\ and dies through the reset
vector. Otherwise the path is zero-terminated for the library's
benefit, and the ProDOS prefix is established: if \textsc{get\_prefix}
returns one, or the startup path is absolute (leading `/'), nothing
needs doing; otherwise the prefix is recovered from the pathname at
[[SYS_PATH]] that ProDOS used to launch this file --- everything up
through the last `/' is copied into [[PREFIX_BUF]] and set via the
library. Finally the startup path is stashed at [[SAVED_PATH]] (a
convention selectors can rely on) and control moves to the page-one
launcher, since the startup file may load right over this code.

<<u1system prefix setup>>=
        ORG $21A6
SYS_STARTUP
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Establish the ProDOS prefix and hand off to LAUNCH_INTRO.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   STARTUP_PATH - length-prefixed startup pathname
        ;   SYS_PATH     - pathname this launcher was started from
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Fail to the reset vector if no startup path. Otherwise
        ;   zero-terminate it, GET_PREFIX; if none and the path is
        ;   relative, copy the volume part of SYS_PATH to PREFIX_BUF
        ;   and SET_PREFIX. Copy the path to SAVED_PATH and jump to
        ;   the page-one launcher.
        LDY STARTUP_PATH
        BNE .have_path
        ; --- no startup file: report and halt ---
        LDA #$0F
        JSR MON_TABV
        LDA #$06
        STA MON_CH
        JSR PRINT_INLINE
        HEX c3 e1 ee a7 f4 a0 e6 e9    ; "Can't fi"
        HEX ee e4 a0 e1 a0 f3 f4 e1    ; "nd a sta"
        HEX f2 f4 f5 f0 a0 e6 e9 ec    ; "rtup fil"
        HEX e5 ae 8d 00                ; "e." CR
        JMP GO_RESET
.have_path
        LDA #$00
        STA STARTUP_PATH+1,Y            ; zero-terminate for the library
        LDA #$C7                        ; MLI GET_PREFIX (-> MLIB_PATH)
        JSR MLIB_MLI
        LDA MLIB_PATH
        BNE .launch                     ; prefix already set
        LDA STARTUP_PATH+1
        AND #$7F
        CMP #$2F                        ; absolute path needs no prefix
        BEQ .launch
        ; --- derive the prefix from our own pathname ---
        LDY SYS_PATH
.find_slash
        LDA SYS_PATH,Y
        AND #$7F
        CMP #$2F                        ; scan back for the last '/'
        BEQ .got_slash
        DEY
        BNE .find_slash
.got_slash
        CPY #$02                        ; "/x..." at minimum
        BCC .launch
        LDA #$00
        STA PREFIX_BUF+1,Y              ; terminate after the slash
.copy   LDA SYS_PATH,Y
        STA PREFIX_BUF,Y
        DEY
        BNE .copy
        JSR MLIB_SET_PREFIX_P
        DC.W PREFIX_BUF+1               ; -> zero-terminated prefix text
.launch
        LDY STARTUP_PATH                ; copy length + path for posterity
.save   LDA STARTUP_PATH,Y
        STA SAVED_PATH,Y
        DEY
        BPL .save
        JMP LAUNCH_INTRO
@ %def SYS_STARTUP

\section{Page-one helpers}
\label{sec:page-one-helpers}

These three routines run at [[$0100]]--[[$016E]], on the (otherwise
unused bottom of the) stack page, so they survive after the startup
file overwrites the launcher. On disk they sit at
[[PAGE1_SRC]]--[[PAGE1_END]]; the [[RORG]] makes every label carry its
run-time address.

[[PRINT_INLINE]] is the inline-string printer used throughout the
launcher: it pops the return address into the self-modified pointer
[[.ptr]], prints high-ASCII characters until a zero terminator, and
returns past it. On machines older than the IIe (ROM id byte
[[$06]]) lowercase is folded to uppercase, since a II+ cannot display
it.

[[LAUNCH_INTRO]] is the actual hand-off: \textsc{brun} the startup
file through the library. The library loads the file at its aux-type
address and calls it; control never comes back unless the load failed
or the program returned, in which case the library's error code is
shown as ``\texttt{<< Startup Error \#\$nn >>}'' and the machine dies
through the reset vector.

<<u1system page one helpers>>=
        ORG $2223
        RORG $0100
PRINT_INLINE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Print the zero-terminated high-ASCII string that follows
        ; the JSR to this routine.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Pop the return address into .ptr, emit characters via
        ;   MON_COUT (folding lowercase on pre-IIe ROMs) until a $00,
        ;   then return to the byte after the terminator.
        ; Clobbers: A, X
        PLA
        STA .ptr
        PLA
        STA .ptr+1
.next   INC .ptr
        BNE .fetch
        INC .ptr+1
.ptr    = *+1
.fetch  LDA $FFFF                       ; (self-modified pointer)
        BEQ .done
        ORA #$80
        LDX ROM_MACHID
        CPX #$06                        ; IIe or later displays lowercase
        BEQ .print
        CMP #$E0
        BCC .print
        AND #$DF                        ; II+: fold to uppercase
.print  JSR MON_COUT
        JMP .next
.done   LDA .ptr+1                      ; return past the terminator
        PHA
        LDA .ptr
        PHA
        RTS
GO_RESET
        ; die through the warm-reset vector
        JMP (RESET_VEC)
LAUNCH_INTRO
        SUBROUTINE
        ; BRUN the startup file; report if it comes back.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   MLIB_BRUN_P on the zero-terminated startup path. If the
        ;   load fails or the program returns, print the library
        ;   error code and reset.
        JSR MLIB_BRUN_P
        DC.W STARTUP_PATH+1             ; -> zero-terminated path text
        PHA                             ; library error code
        LDA #$0F
        JSR MON_TABV
        LDA #$07
        STA MON_CH
        JSR PRINT_INLINE
        HEX bc bc a0 d3 f4 e1 f2 f4    ; "<< Start"
        HEX f5 f0 a0 c5 f2 f2 ef f2    ; "up Error"
        HEX a0 a3 a4 a0 a0 a0 be be    ; " #$   >>"
        HEX 00
        LDA #$1A
        STA MON_CH                      ; position over the blanks
        PLA
        JSR MON_PRBYTE
        JSR MON_CROUT
        JMP GO_RESET
        REND
@ %def PRINT_INLINE GO_RESET LAUNCH_INTRO

\section{The file library: interface}
\label{sec:mlib-interface}

The resident library at [[$B700]] is the game's entire disk interface
from here on --- \texttt{MI.U1} and the overlays call these vectors,
never the MLI directly. The design is a 6502 classic: every call is a
[[JSR]] to a fixed vector followed by \emph{inline arguments} in the
instruction stream; the library pops the return address to read them
and returns past them, with carry set and an error code in A on
failure (X and Y are preserved). Each pathname-taking function exists
in two flavors: the base form takes the zero-terminated pathname text
itself inline, and the \texttt{\_P} form takes an inline 16-bit
pointer to the text --- which is what callers use for variable paths.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\ra{1.1}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}llll@{}}
\toprule
\thead{Vector} & \thead{Name} & \thead{Inline args} & \thead{Action} \\
\midrule
[[$B700]] & [[MLIB_MLI]] & --- & raw MLI call, command in A \\
[[$B703]] & [[MLIB_BLOAD]] & path & load BIN file at its aux address \\
[[$B706]] & [[MLIB_BLOAD_AT]] & addr.w, path & load BIN file at addr \\
[[$B709]] & [[MLIB_BSAVE]] & addr.w, len.w, path & create/write BIN file \\
[[$B70C]] & [[MLIB_BRUN]] & path & load at aux address and call \\
[[$B70F]] & [[MLIB_SET_PREFIX]] & path & set ProDOS prefix \\
[[$B712]] & [[MLIB_QUIT]] & --- & close all, jump to reset \\
[[$B715]] & [[MLIB_READ_BLOCK]] & ptr.w to block\# & read disk block to [[MLIB_IOBUF]] \\
[[$B718]] & [[MLIB_WRITE_BLOCK]] & ptr.w to block\# & write [[MLIB_IOBUF]] to block \\
[[$B71B]] & [[MLIB_SET_UNIT]] & --- & unit number := A \\
[[$B71E]] & [[MLIB_BLOAD_P]] & pathptr.w & as [[MLIB_BLOAD]] \\
[[$B721]] & [[MLIB_BLOAD_AT_P]] & addr.w, pathptr.w & as [[MLIB_BLOAD_AT]] \\
[[$B724]] & [[MLIB_BSAVE_P]] & addr.w, len.w, pathptr.w & as [[MLIB_BSAVE]] \\
[[$B727]] & [[MLIB_BRUN_P]] & pathptr.w & as [[MLIB_BRUN]] \\
[[$B72A]] & [[MLIB_SET_PREFIX_P]] & pathptr.w & as [[MLIB_SET_PREFIX]] \\
[[$B72D]] & [[MLIB_DESTROY]] & path & delete a file \\
[[$B730]] & [[MLIB_DESTROY_P]] & pathptr.w & as [[MLIB_DESTROY]] \\
[[$B733]] & [[MLIB_PARSE_PATH]] & path & copy path to [[MLIB_PATH]] only \\
[[$B736]] & [[MLIB_PARSE_PATH_P]] & pathptr.w & as [[MLIB_PARSE_PATH]] \\
[[$B739]] & [[MLIB_BUZZ]] & --- & error buzz \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{The resident file library's call vectors. ``path'' = inline
zero-terminated pathname; ``.w'' = inline 16-bit word.}
\label{tab:mlib-vectors}
\end{table}

File loads and saves insist on file type \texttt{BIN} and files no
longer than 64K; loads use the file's recorded aux-type load address
unless the \texttt{\_AT} form supplies one. \textsc{bsave} creates the
file (type BIN, aux = address) if it does not exist, and updates the
catalog's aux type and EOF afterward. Errors are translated from MLI
codes into the game's own error numbers
(table~\ref{tab:mlib-errors}) and buzz the speaker twice unless
[[MLIB_QUIET]] has its high bit set.

<<mlib jump table>>=
        ORG $2292
        RORG $B700
MLIB_MLI            JMP MLI_CALL
MLIB_BLOAD          JMP DO_BLOAD
MLIB_BLOAD_AT       JMP DO_BLOAD_AT
MLIB_BSAVE          JMP DO_BSAVE
MLIB_BRUN           JMP DO_BRUN
MLIB_SET_PREFIX     JMP DO_SET_PREFIX
MLIB_QUIT           JMP DO_QUIT
MLIB_READ_BLOCK     JMP DO_READ_BLOCK
MLIB_WRITE_BLOCK    JMP DO_WRITE_BLOCK
MLIB_SET_UNIT       JMP DO_SET_UNIT
MLIB_BLOAD_P        JMP DO_BLOAD_P
MLIB_BLOAD_AT_P     JMP DO_BLOAD_AT_P
MLIB_BSAVE_P        JMP DO_BSAVE_P
MLIB_BRUN_P         JMP DO_BRUN_P
MLIB_SET_PREFIX_P   JMP DO_SET_PREFIX_P
MLIB_DESTROY        JMP DO_DESTROY
MLIB_DESTROY_P      JMP DO_DESTROY_P
MLIB_PARSE_PATH     JMP DO_PARSE
MLIB_PARSE_PATH_P   JMP DO_PARSE_P
MLIB_BUZZ           JMP DO_BUZZ
; --- library state ---
MLIB_QUIET          DC.B $00    ; bit 7 set: suppress the error buzz
MLIB_FN             DC.B $00    ; function code as called (bit 7 = ptr args)
MLIB_FNUM           DC.B $00    ; function code & $3F
MLIB_ADDR           DC.W $0000  ; caller-supplied load/save address
MLIB_LEN            DC.W $0000  ; caller-supplied save length
MLIB_ERR            DC.B $00    ; last translated error code (0 = ok)
MLIB_LASTCMD        DC.B $00    ; MLI command of the last failure
MLIB_MLIERR         DC.B $00    ; raw MLI error of the last failure
MLIB_XREG           DC.B $00    ; caller's X, restored on return
MLIB_YREG           DC.B $00    ; caller's Y, restored on return
        REND
@ %def MLIB_MLI MLIB_BLOAD MLIB_BLOAD_AT MLIB_BSAVE MLIB_BRUN
@ %def MLIB_SET_PREFIX MLIB_QUIT MLIB_READ_BLOCK MLIB_WRITE_BLOCK
@ %def MLIB_SET_UNIT MLIB_BLOAD_P MLIB_BLOAD_AT_P MLIB_BSAVE_P MLIB_BRUN_P
@ %def MLIB_SET_PREFIX_P MLIB_DESTROY MLIB_DESTROY_P MLIB_PARSE_PATH
@ %def MLIB_PARSE_PATH_P MLIB_BUZZ MLIB_QUIET MLIB_FN MLIB_FNUM MLIB_ADDR
@ %def MLIB_LEN MLIB_ERR MLIB_LASTCMD MLIB_MLIERR MLIB_XREG MLIB_YREG

\section{The file library: load, save, run}

The function bodies share three building blocks: [[SAVE_ARGS]]
captures registers and takes over the caller's return address as the
inline-argument pointer; [[GET_PATHNAME]] copies the pathname (inline
text or via inline pointer, per the function code's high bit) into
[[MLIB_PATH]]; and [[OPEN_XFER]] does the type/access checks, OPEN,
and READ or WRITE. Every body funnels out through [[EPILOGUE]], which
pushes the advanced argument pointer back on the stack so the final
[[RTS]] lands after the inline arguments.

<<mlib load save run>>=
        ORG $22DA
        RORG $B748
DO_BLOAD_P
        SUBROUTINE
        ; BLOAD at the file's aux address (path via pointer / text).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Capture args, fetch pathname, GET_FILE_INFO, then open
        ;   and read with required access $01. Out via EPILOGUE.
        LDA #$82
        BNE .save
DO_BLOAD
        LDA #$02
.save   JSR SAVE_ARGS
LOAD_COMMON
        JSR GET_PATHNAME
        JSR MLI_GET_INFO
        BCS .done
        LDA #$01                        ; need read access
        JSR OPEN_XFER
.done   JMP EPILOGUE
DO_BLOAD_AT_P
        SUBROUTINE
        ; BLOAD at an explicitly supplied address.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Fetch the inline address word into MLIB_ADDR, then join
        ;   LOAD_COMMON (info, open, read). Out via EPILOGUE.
        LDA #$83
        BNE .save
DO_BLOAD_AT
        LDA #$03
.save   JSR SAVE_ARGS
        JSR GET_ARG_ADDR
        JMP LOAD_COMMON
DO_BSAVE_P
        SUBROUTINE
        ; BSAVE: create if needed, write, fix up catalog info.
        ;
        ; Inputs (inline): addr.w, len.w, then path text or pointer.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   If GET_FILE_INFO fails, CREATE type BIN with aux = addr,
        ;   access $C3, seedling. Then open and WRITE with required
        ;   access $02. Out via EPILOGUE.
        LDA #$84
        BNE .save
DO_BSAVE
        LDA #$04
.save   JSR SAVE_ARGS
        JSR GET_ARG_ADDR
        JSR GET_ARG_LEN
        JSR GET_PATHNAME
        JSR MLI_GET_INFO
        BCC .exists
        LDX MLIB_ADDR                   ; create: aux type <- address
        STX PARM_CREATE+5
        LDY MLIB_ADDR+1
        STY PARM_CREATE+6
        LDA #$06                        ; file type BIN
        STA PARM_CREATE+4
        LDX #$C3                        ; access: destroy/rename/write/read
        LDY #$01                        ; storage: seedling
        STX PARM_CREATE+3
        STY PARM_CREATE+7
        LDA #$C0                        ; MLI CREATE
        JSR MLI_CALL
        BCS EPILOGUE
        JSR MLI_GET_INFO
        BCS EPILOGUE
.exists LDA #$02                        ; need write access
        JSR OPEN_XFER
        ; falls through to EPILOGUE
EPILOGUE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Common exit: A = error code, carry = error flag.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Store the code in MLIB_ERR; on error buzz twice and close
        ;   everything. Push the advanced inline-arg pointer so RTS
        ;   returns past the arguments; restore caller X/Y.
        STA MLIB_ERR
        BCC .ok
        JSR DO_BUZZ
        JSR DO_BUZZ
        JSR CLOSE_ALL
        SEC
.ok     LDA MLIB_INLINE_PTR+1
        PHA
        LDA MLIB_INLINE_PTR
        PHA
        LDA MLIB_ERR
        LDX MLIB_XREG
        LDY MLIB_YREG
        RTS
DO_BRUN_P
        SUBROUTINE
        ; BRUN: load a BIN file at its aux address and call it.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   As BLOAD, then push the return point, restore the
        ;   caller's X/Y, and JSR through the load address. Returns
        ;   (A=0, carry clear) only if the program itself returns.
        LDA #$81
        BNE .save
DO_BRUN
        LDA #$01
.save   JSR SAVE_ARGS
        JSR GET_PATHNAME
        JSR MLI_GET_INFO
        BCS EPILOGUE
        LDA #$01                        ; need read access
        JSR OPEN_XFER
        BCS EPILOGUE
        LDA MLIB_INLINE_PTR+1           ; return past the inline args
        PHA
        LDA MLIB_INLINE_PTR
        PHA
        LDX MLIB_XREG
        LDY MLIB_YREG
        JSR CALL_LOADED
        CLC
        LDA #$00
        RTS
CALL_LOADED
        ; dispatch into the freshly loaded program
        JMP (PARM_RW+2)
        REND
@ %def DO_BLOAD_P DO_BLOAD LOAD_COMMON DO_BLOAD_AT_P DO_BLOAD_AT
@ %def DO_BSAVE_P DO_BSAVE EPILOGUE DO_BRUN_P DO_BRUN CALL_LOADED

\section{The file library: open and transfer}

[[OPEN_XFER]] is the heart of every load and save. A on entry is the
required access bit (read [[$01]] or write [[$02]]); the function
number distinguishes BSAVE (function 4, [[WRITE]] + catalog fixup)
from the loads ([[READ]]). Functions below 3 take the destination
from the file's own aux type; 3 and up use the caller's address. For
reads, the transfer length is the file's EOF --- rejected if over
64K.

<<mlib open and transfer>>=
        ORG $2396
        RORG $B804
OPEN_XFER
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Open MLIB_PATH and READ or WRITE its data.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A          - required access bit ($01 read, $02 write)
        ;   MLIB_FNUM  - function: <3 load at aux, 3 load at addr,
        ;                4 save
        ;   PARM_INFO  - filled by a preceding GET_FILE_INFO
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Verify type BIN and access; OPEN; aim PARM_RW at the
        ;   destination; length = EOF (reads, <=64K) or MLIB_LEN
        ;   (writes); READ or WRITE; for saves update aux type and
        ;   EOF in the catalog; CLOSE.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   carry set + error code in A on failure
        LDX #$06                        ; required file type: BIN
        JSR CHECK_OPEN
        BCS .out
        LDA MLIB_FNUM
        LDX MLIB_ADDR
        LDY MLIB_ADDR+1
        CMP #$03
        BCS .have_addr                  ; fn >= 3: caller's address
        LDX PARM_INFO+5                 ; else the file's aux type
        LDY PARM_INFO+6
.have_addr
        STX PARM_RW+2
        STY PARM_RW+3
        LDX MLIB_LEN
        LDY MLIB_LEN+1
        CMP #$04
        BEQ .set_len                    ; saves use the caller's length
        LDA #$D1                        ; MLI GET_EOF
        JSR MLI_CALL
        BCS .out
        LDX PARM_EOF+2                  ; reads use the file length
        LDY PARM_EOF+3
        LDA PARM_EOF+4
        BEQ .set_len
        LDA #$0E                        ; file longer than 64K
        SEC
        RTS
.set_len
        STX PARM_RW+4
        STY PARM_RW+5
        LDX MLIB_FNUM
        LDA #$CA                        ; MLI READ
        CPX #$04
        BNE .go
        LDA #$CB                        ; MLI WRITE
        JSR MLI_CALL
        BCS .out
        ; --- after a save: record aux type and EOF in the catalog ---
        LDA MLIB_ADDR+1
        STA PARM_INFO+6
        LDA MLIB_ADDR
        STA PARM_INFO+5
        JSR MLI_SET_INFO
        BCS .out
        LDA #$00
        STA PARM_EOF+4
        LDA PARM_RW+7                   ; EOF <- bytes actually written
        STA PARM_EOF+3
        LDA PARM_RW+6
        STA PARM_EOF+2
        LDA #$D0                        ; MLI SET_EOF
.go     JSR MLI_CALL
        BCS .out
        JSR MLI_CLOSE
.out    RTS
        REND
@ %def OPEN_XFER

\section{The file library: prefix, delete, quit, raw blocks}

<<mlib prefix destroy quit blocks>>=
        ORG $2419
        RORG $B887
DO_SET_PREFIX_P
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Set the ProDOS prefix from the inline pathname.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   SET_PREFIX on MLIB_PATH; on success re-seed MLIB_UNIT
        ;   from GP_DEVNUM. Out via EPILOGUE.
        LDA #$85
        BNE .save
DO_SET_PREFIX
        LDA #$05
.save   JSR SAVE_ARGS
        JSR GET_PATHNAME
        LDA #$C6                        ; MLI SET_PREFIX
        JSR MLI_CALL
        BCS .done
        LDX GP_DEVNUM
        STX MLIB_UNIT
.done   JMP EPILOGUE
DO_DESTROY_P
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Delete the named file.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Fetch the pathname, MLI DESTROY, out via EPILOGUE.
        LDA #$88
        BNE .save
DO_DESTROY
        LDA #$08
.save   JSR SAVE_ARGS
        JSR GET_PATHNAME
        LDA #$C1                        ; MLI DESTROY
        JSR MLI_CALL
        JMP EPILOGUE
DO_QUIT
        ; close every file and die through the reset vector
        JSR CLOSE_ALL
        JMP (RESET_VEC)
DO_READ_BLOCK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Read (or write) one 512-byte disk block.
        ;
        ; Inputs (inline): pointer to a 16-bit block number.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Patch READ_BLOCK/WRITE_BLOCK into the MLI call below;
        ;   fetch the block number through the inline pointer into
        ;   PARM_BLOCK; transfer via MLIB_IOBUF on unit MLIB_UNIT.
        LDA #$86
        JSR SAVE_ARGS
        LDA #$80                        ; MLI READ_BLOCK
        BNE .common
DO_WRITE_BLOCK
        LDA #$87
        JSR SAVE_ARGS
        LDA #$81                        ; MLI WRITE_BLOCK
.common STA .cmd
        JSR GET_ARG_BLOCKNUM
        STX PARM_BLOCK+4
        STY PARM_BLOCK+5
        JSR MLI
.cmd    DC.B $00                        ; command byte (self-modified)
        DC.W PARM_BLOCK
TO_EPILOGUE
        JMP EPILOGUE
DO_SET_UNIT
        ; unit number for block I/O <- A
        STA MLIB_UNIT
        CLC
        RTS
SAVE_ARGS
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Capture a call's context.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A  - function code (bit 7 = pointer-style path argument)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Save A (raw and masked) and X/Y; steal the caller's
        ;   return address into MLIB_INLINE_PTR (the inline-argument
        ;   cursor), keeping our own return on the stack.
        STA MLIB_FN
        AND #$3F
        STA MLIB_FNUM
        STX MLIB_XREG
        STY MLIB_YREG
        PLA                             ; our own return address...
        TAY
        PLA
        TAX
        PLA                             ; ...the caller's return becomes
        STA MLIB_INLINE_PTR             ;    the inline-argument cursor
        PLA
        STA MLIB_INLINE_PTR+1
        TXA
        PHA
        TYA
        PHA
        RTS
        REND
@ %def DO_SET_PREFIX_P DO_SET_PREFIX DO_DESTROY_P DO_DESTROY DO_QUIT
@ %def DO_READ_BLOCK DO_WRITE_BLOCK TO_EPILOGUE DO_SET_UNIT SAVE_ARGS

\section{The file library: pathnames and inline arguments}

The inline-argument machinery: [[GET_INLINE]] pre-increments
[[MLIB_INLINE_PTR]] and fetches the next argument byte;
[[GET_INDIRECT]] post-increments a second self-modified pointer
([[MLIB_STR_PTR]]) for reading pathname text via pointer.
[[GET_PATHNAME]] selects one of the two as the character source
(self-modifying the [[JSR]] operand at [[MLIB_GETCHAR_VEC]]) and
copies the zero-terminated text into [[MLIB_PATH]] as a
length-prefixed ProDOS pathname.

<<mlib pathname and inline args>>=
        ORG $2498
        RORG $B906
DO_PARSE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Parse a pathname into MLIB_PATH without touching the disk.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Capture args, copy the pathname argument to MLIB_PATH,
        ;   return success via EPILOGUE.
        LDA #$00
        BEQ .save
DO_PARSE_P
        LDA #$80
.save   JSR SAVE_ARGS
        JSR GET_PATHNAME
        CLC
        BCC TO_EPILOGUE
GET_PATHNAME
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Copy the call's pathname argument into MLIB_PATH.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   MLIB_FN - bit 7 set: inline pointer to text; clear:
        ;             text itself is inline
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Point the fetch JSR at GET_INLINE or GET_INDIRECT, then
        ;   copy bytes until $00, storing length at MLIB_PATH.
        LDX #<GET_INLINE
        LDY #>GET_INLINE
        BIT MLIB_FN
        BPL .set
        JSR GET_INLINE_WORD             ; pointer-style: fetch the pointer
        STX MLIB_STR_PTR
        STY MLIB_STR_PTR+1
        LDX #<GET_INDIRECT
        LDY #>GET_INDIRECT
.set    STX MLIB_GETCHAR_VEC
        STY MLIB_GETCHAR_VEC+1
        LDX #$FF
.loop   INX
MLIB_GETCHAR_VEC = *+1
        JSR GET_INLINE                  ; (self-modified source)
        BEQ .done
        STA MLIB_PATH+1,X
        BNE .loop
.done   STX MLIB_PATH
        RTS
GET_INLINE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Fetch the next inline-argument byte.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Pre-increment MLIB_INLINE_PTR (the captured caller return
        ;   address) and load the byte it points at.
        INC MLIB_INLINE_PTR
        BNE .go
        INC MLIB_INLINE_PTR+1
MLIB_INLINE_PTR = *+1
.go     LDA $FFFF                       ; (self-modified cursor)
        RTS
GET_INDIRECT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Fetch the next pathname byte through the string pointer.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Load via MLIB_STR_PTR, post-increment it, and compare
        ;   against zero so Z flags the terminator for the caller.
MLIB_STR_PTR = *+1
        LDA $FFFF                       ; (self-modified pointer)
        INC MLIB_STR_PTR
        BNE .go
        INC MLIB_STR_PTR+1
.go     CMP #$00
        RTS
GET_INLINE_WORD
        ; next two inline bytes -> X (lo), Y (hi)
        JSR GET_INLINE
        TAX
        JSR GET_INLINE
        TAY
        RTS
GET_ARG_ADDR
        ; inline word -> MLIB_ADDR
        JSR GET_INLINE_WORD
        STX MLIB_ADDR
        STY MLIB_ADDR+1
        RTS
GET_ARG_LEN
        ; inline word -> MLIB_LEN
        JSR GET_INLINE_WORD
        STX MLIB_LEN
        STY MLIB_LEN+1
        RTS
GET_ARG_BLOCKNUM
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Fetch a block number through an inline pointer.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   The inline word is the ADDRESS of a 16-bit block number;
        ;   read it and return the number in X (lo) / Y (hi).
        JSR GET_INLINE_WORD
        STX .src
        STY .src+1
        LDY #$01
.src    = *+1
.get    LDA $FFFF,Y                     ; (self-modified pointer)
        PHA
        DEY
        BPL .get
        PLA
        TAX
        PLA
        TAY
        RTS
        REND
@ %def DO_PARSE DO_PARSE_P GET_PATHNAME GET_INLINE GET_INDIRECT
@ %def GET_INLINE_WORD GET_ARG_ADDR GET_ARG_LEN GET_ARG_BLOCKNUM
@ %def MLIB_INLINE_PTR MLIB_STR_PTR MLIB_GETCHAR_VEC

\section{The file library: file info and open checks}

<<mlib file info and open checks>>=
        ORG $2522
        RORG $B990
MLI_GET_INFO
        SUBROUTINE
        ; GET_FILE_INFO on MLIB_PATH into PARM_INFO.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Set the parameter count for GET ($0A) or SET ($07,
        ;   second entry, with nulled modification date) and issue
        ;   the MLI call through MLI_CALL.
        LDY #$0A                        ; parameter count for GET
        LDA #$C4                        ; MLI GET_FILE_INFO
        BNE .go
MLI_SET_INFO
        ; SET_FILE_INFO from PARM_INFO, nulling the modification date
        LDA #$00
        LDX #$03
.clr    STA PARM_INFO+10,X              ; null modification date/time
        DEX
        BPL .clr
        LDY #$07                        ; parameter count for SET
        LDA #$C3                        ; MLI SET_FILE_INFO
.go     STY PARM_INFO
        JMP MLI_CALL
CHECK_OPEN
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Validate the file and open it.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   X - required file type ($06 BIN)
        ;   A - required access bit ($01 read / $02 write)
        ;   PARM_INFO - from a preceding GET_FILE_INFO
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Type or access mismatch fails with the game's own codes
        ;   $0D / $0A. Otherwise MLI OPEN; copy the ref number into
        ;   the read/write, close, and EOF parameter blocks.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   carry set + error code in A on failure
        CPX PARM_INFO+4
        BNE .badtype
        AND PARM_INFO+3
        BEQ .locked
        LDA #$C8                        ; MLI OPEN
        JSR MLI_CALL
        BCS .out
        LDA PARM_OPEN+5                 ; ref number feeds three parm blocks
        STA PARM_RW+1
        STA PARM_CLOSE+1
        STA PARM_EOF+1
.out    RTS
.badtype
        LDA #$0D                        ; wrong file type
        SEC
        RTS
.locked LDA #$0A                        ; access denied
        SEC
        RTS
        REND
@ %def MLI_GET_INFO MLI_SET_INFO CHECK_OPEN

\section{The file library: close and the error buzz}

<<mlib close and beep>>=
        ORG $2562
        RORG $B9D0
CLOSE_ALL
        ; close every open file (ref number 0)
        LDA #$00
        STA PARM_CLOSE+1
MLI_CLOSE
        ; MLI CLOSE on PARM_CLOSE
        LDA #$CC
        JMP MLI_CALL
DO_BUZZ
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Sound the error buzz.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Unless MLIB_QUIET bit 7 is set, pulse the speaker $20
        ;   times with uneven spacing (a harsh buzz), interrupts
        ;   masked so the pitch stays steady.
        BIT MLIB_QUIET
        BMI .out
        PHP
        SEI                             ; keep the pitch steady
        LDA #$20
        STA .count
.loop   LDA #$02
        JSR MON_WAIT
        STA SPEAKER
        LDA #$24
        JSR MON_WAIT
        STA SPEAKER
        DEC .count
        BNE .loop
        PLP
.out    RTS
.count  DC.B $00
        REND
@ %def CLOSE_ALL MLI_CLOSE DO_BUZZ

\section{The file library: MLI dispatch and error translation}

Every MLI command the library issues goes through [[MLI_CALL]]: the
command byte and the address of its parameter block (all blocks live
in one page, low bytes from [[PARM_LO_TBL]] indexed by the command's
low five bits) are patched into an inline [[JSR MLI]] frame. On
failure, the raw MLI error is recorded and translated through a pair
of tables into the game's own error numbering.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\ra{1.05}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\thead{MLI error} & \thead{Meaning} & \thead{Game code} \\
\midrule
\$28 & no device connected & \$03 \\
\$2B & disk write protected & \$04 \\
\$40 & invalid pathname syntax & \$10 \\
\$41, \$42 & file control block / too many files & \$0C \\
\$43 & invalid reference number & \$12 \\
\$44, \$45 & path / volume not found & \$06 \\
\$46 & file not found & \$07 \\
\$47 & duplicate filename & \$13 \\
\$48 & volume full & \$09 \\
\$49 & directory full & \$11 \\
\$4B & unsupported storage type & \$0D \\
\$4C & end of file & \$05 \\
\$4D & position out of range & \$02 \\
\$4E & access denied & \$0A \\
\$50 & file open & \$14 \\
\$53 & invalid parameter & \$0B \\
\$56 & bad buffer address & \$0C \\
(other) & --- & \$08 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{MLI-to-game error code translation. The library also issues
\$0D (wrong type), \$0A (locked), and \$0E (file over 64K) directly.}
\label{tab:mlib-errors}
\end{table}

<<mlib mli dispatch>>=
        ORG $2590
        RORG $B9FE
MLI_CALL
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Issue MLI command A with its canonical parameter block.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A - MLI command byte; its parameter block must have been
        ;       prepared at the page-$BA address in PARM_LO_TBL
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Patch command and parameter pointer into the JSR MLI
        ;   frame below. On error, record raw code and command, then
        ;   translate via MLI_ERR_TBL -> APP_ERR_TBL.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   carry set + translated error code in A on failure
        STA .cmd
        AND #$1F
        TAX
        LDA PARM_LO_TBL,X
        STA .parm
        JSR MLI
.cmd    DC.B $00                        ; command byte (self-modified)
.parm   DC.B $7A                        ; parm block low byte (self-modified)
        DC.B $BA                        ; all parameter blocks sit in page $BA
        BCS .err
        RTS
.err    STA MLIB_MLIERR
        LDY .cmd
        STY MLIB_LASTCMD
        LDX #$12
.scan   CMP MLI_ERR_TBL,X
        BEQ .got
        DEX
        BPL .scan
        LDX #$13                        ; unknown: default code
.got    LDA APP_ERR_TBL,X
        SEC
        RTS
        REND
@ %def MLI_CALL

<<mlib dispatch tables>>=
        ORG $25BF
        RORG $BA2D
PARM_LO_TBL                             ; parm block low byte per cmd & $1F
        HEX bb c7 ca cf cf e1 c7 c7    ; CREATE DESTROY RENAME SET/GET_INFO
        HEX e6 ec f0 f0 f8 f8 e1 e1    ; ON_LINE S/G_PREFIX OPEN NEWLINE R/W
        HEX e1 e1 e1 e1                ; CLOSE FLUSH S/G_MARK S/G_EOF S/G_BUF
MLI_ERR_TBL                             ; recognized MLI error codes
        HEX 28 2b 40 41 42 43 44 45
        HEX 46 47 48 49 4b 4c 4d 4e
        HEX 50 53 56
APP_ERR_TBL                             ; game error code per table above
        HEX 03 04 10 0c 0c 12 06 06
        HEX 07 13 09 11 0d 05 02 0a
        HEX 14 0b 0c 08
        DS.B 17,$00                     ; unused
        REND
@ %def PARM_LO_TBL MLI_ERR_TBL APP_ERR_TBL

\section{The file library: pathname buffer and parameter blocks}

All MLI parameter blocks live in page [[$BA]], pre-initialized on disk
with their parameter counts and fixed pointers; the per-call fields
(ref numbers, lengths, addresses) are filled in at run time. Several
blocks are shared between commands of identical shape ---
[[PARM_PATHONLY]] serves \textsc{destroy} and both prefix calls, and
[[PARM_EOF]] serves \textsc{on\_line}, \textsc{set/get\_mark},
\textsc{set/get\_eof}, and \textsc{set/get\_buf}.

<<mlib path buffer and parameter blocks>>=
        ORG $260B
        RORG $BA79
MLIB_PATH
        DS.B 66,$00                     ; length-prefixed pathname buffer
PARM_CREATE
        DC.B $07                        ; CREATE: 7 parameters
        DC.W MLIB_PATH
        DC.B $C3                        ; access
        DC.B $00                        ; file type (set per call)
        DC.W $0000                      ; aux type (set per call)
        DC.B $00                        ; storage type (set per call)
        DC.W $0000                      ; create date
        DC.W $0000                      ; create time
PARM_PATHONLY
        DC.B $01                        ; DESTROY / SET_PREFIX / GET_PREFIX
        DC.W MLIB_PATH
PARM_RENAME
        DC.B $02                        ; RENAME (unused by the launcher)
        DC.W MLIB_PATH
        DC.W $0200                      ; new name: parsed input buffer
PARM_INFO
        DC.B $00                        ; GET/SET_FILE_INFO: count set per call
        DC.W MLIB_PATH
        DS.B 15,$00                     ; access,type,aux,storage,blocks,dates
PARM_EOF
        DC.B $02                        ; EOF/MARK/BUF/ON_LINE: 2 parameters
        DC.B $00                        ; ref number
        HEX 00 00 00                    ; 3-byte EOF / mark value
PARM_OPEN
        DC.B $03                        ; OPEN: 3 parameters
        DC.W MLIB_PATH
        DC.W MLIB_IOBUF                 ; the library's 1K file buffer
        DC.B $00                        ; -> ref number
PARM_NEWLINE
        DC.B $03                        ; NEWLINE (unused by the launcher)
        DC.B $00                        ; ref number
        DC.B $7F                        ; enable mask
        DC.B $0D                        ; newline char
PARM_RW
        DC.B $04                        ; READ/WRITE: 4 parameters
        DC.B $00                        ; ref number
        DC.W $0000                      ; data buffer (the load address)
        DC.W $0000                      ; request count
        DC.W $0000                      ; -> transfer count
PARM_CLOSE
        DC.B $01                        ; CLOSE: 1 parameter
        DC.B $00                        ; ref number (0 = all)
PARM_BLOCK
        DC.B $03                        ; READ/WRITE_BLOCK: 3 parameters
MLIB_UNIT
        DC.B $00                        ; unit number (seeded from DEVNUM)
        DC.W MLIB_IOBUF                 ; block buffer
        DC.W $0000                      ; block number
        REND
@ %def MLIB_PATH PARM_CREATE PARM_PATHONLY PARM_RENAME PARM_INFO PARM_EOF
@ %def PARM_OPEN PARM_NEWLINE PARM_RW PARM_CLOSE PARM_BLOCK MLIB_UNIT

