\chapter{Title and introduction: U1.INTRO}

\texttt{U1.INTRO} is the animated title sequence: the castle of Lord
British is painted piece by piece on the hi-res screen while a tune
plays, a bird crosses the sky, a banner unfurls, and the picture
finally dissolves into the title image. It runs in a loop as an
attract mode --- any key launches the game proper (\textsc{brun}
\texttt{MI.U1}); ESC pauses.

Two facts shape the code. First, on cold start it \textsc{brun}s
\texttt{MAKE.INDATA}, which builds the intro's artwork in memory
(the pixel data the animation draws from lives at
[[ART_BASE]]--[[$8Fxx]] % TODO-SYM: upper bound after makeindata RE
and is \emph{not} part of this file); until that program is reverse
engineered, the art tables here are named by the routine that consumes
them. Second, nearly every drawing loop is built around
\emph{self-modified operands}: a stream pointer patched into an
absolute [[LDA]], and row/column limits patched into [[CPY]]/[[CPX]]
immediates. The annotations name each patched byte with the
[[= *+1]] idiom.

The animation engine is a frame loop ([[ANIM_RUN]]) that calls a fixed
list of per-frame actors; each actor decides from its own state
variables (the [[V_]] block) whether to do anything this frame. The
show is divided into \emph{steps} 0--4; [[SET_STEP]] redraws the base
picture from one of five progressively more complete frames
([[STEP_IMG_PTRS]]), and the actors fill in the differences ---
exactly the structure of a cartoon: key frames plus in-betweens.

